<HEADLINE>
FT  28 OCT 94 / Views sought on rail access charges
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By CHARLES BATCHELOR, Transport Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Mr John Swift QC, the rail industry regulator, yesterday asked the railway
freight industry for its views on how track access charges should be
negotiated with Railtrack.
He outlined in a consultation document his own proposals to allow the two
sides to negotiate commercial rates while at the same time setting limits on
charges to companies with no alternative.
As part of the privatisation of British Rail train operations and track
ownership have been split and train operators pay Railtrack depending on the
number and type of trains that they run.
In a departure from his earlier proposals for passenger train operators, Mr
Swift said there was no clear case for requiring Railtrack to reduce charges
to freight operators by a formula based on the retail price index minus a
particular figure. Commercial pressures should ensure that Railtrack passed
on any cost savings, he said.
He proposed a method of calculating appropriate cost 'floors' and price
ceilings which would allow Railtrack to cover its costs but not penalise
customers. 'Railtrack's current approach to calculating ceilings may not
provide users with adequate protection against excessive charges,' he
warned.
The regulator said he would require Railtrack to publish more information
about its freight business so that he could see whether his guidance had
been followed.
Responses to the consultation document are required by November 25.
Framework for the Approval of Railtrack's Track Access Charges for Freight
Services. Office of the Rail Regulator, 1 Waterhouse Square, Holborn Bars,
138-142 Holborn, London EC1N 2SU. Free.
</TEXT>
