<HEADLINE>
FT  28 OCT 94 / Bidders join Channel 5 licence queue
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By RAYMOND SNODDY
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
The Independent Television Commission will formally advertise the licence
for Channel 5 on Tuesday as interest appears to be growing in a service that
has taken years to get off the ground.
The ITC confirmed yesterday that it would have to advertise two separate
propositions for the channel - one which would reach just over half the UK
population, and the other nearly three-quarters.
The reason for the uncertainty is that the ITC is still applying for
international permission to use extra frequencies for Channel 5. The new
permissions are necessary because the government set aside frequencies
previously allotted for the new channel for the possible future development
of digital terrestrial television.
But in spite of the uncertainty there is considerable interest. Mr Izzy
Asper, chairman and chief executive of CanWest Global Communications, the
Canadian broadcaster with television interests in New Zealand, Australia and
Chile, said he would bid for the channel 'as long as there are no nasty
surprises' in next week's ITC announcement.
Mr Asper, who has been negotiating with a number of big UK media and leisure
companies, would plan to broadcast a high proportion of British-made
programmes if he won the Channel 5 franchise. CanWest usually works closely
with independent producers - allowing them to retain international
distribution rights to their programmes.
White Rose, the consortium that tried to unseat Yorkshire Television in the
last ITV franchise round, is also interested in bidding.
Mr William Lewisham, a director of White Rose, a consortium which includes
RTE, the Irish national broadcaster, and City financial interests, said
yesterday that the prospects were interesting as long as the channel could
reach more than 60 per cent of the population.
Mr Ward Thomas, the chairman of Yorkshire-Tyne Tees Television, has found
considerable interest in the channel from potential US partners.
The other big groups expressing interest range from Channel 5 Broadcasting,
which brings together Time Warner, MAI and Pearson, owner of the Financial
Times, a grouping led by NBC, the US network, and Mr Richard Branson's
Virgin Group.
But the number of bids will probably depend on the fine print of the ITC
document and how optimistic Sir George Russell, the ITC chairman, is about
getting permission to use new frequencies.
</TEXT>
