<HEADLINE>
FT  28 OCT 94 / Political Notebook: A forgotten war in the Balkans
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PHILIP STEPHENS
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Sleaze, ministerial resignations, more sleaze. Post Office privatisation,
Europe. The odd MP is even thinking ahead to Mr Kenneth Clarke's Budget. The
one thing no one at Westminster is talking about is Bosnia.
The conflict has slipped from the front to foreign news pages. Television
news programmes have become bored with images from a still-besieged but, in
Bosnian terms, half-normal Sarejevo.
The soon-to-depart General Sir Michael Rose, the British commander of the
United Nations forces, merits still the occasional radio interview. But the
average MP has forgotten that 3,500 British troops are spending a third
winter helping to keep the fragile peace in the former Yugoslav province.
Across the road from the House of Commons at the Foreign Office there are
different priorities. For two months now, Bosnia has been Mr Douglas Hurd's
principal preoccupation - so much so that he occasionally asks himself
whether it has become an unhealthy obsession.
It has not. A few weeks ago Mr Hurd feared the biggest rift in
Anglo-American relations since Suez. The prospect was removed, but only
temporarily, by the Moslem Bosnian government's decision to suspend until
next spring its demand for the UN to lift the international arms embargo.
Had it not done so, Washington would have forced a vote in the security
council. London would have abstained and, assuming the embargo was lifted,
would have ordered an immediate withdrawal of British troops. The French
would have done likewise. The five-nation contract, which includes also
Russia and Germany, would have fractured.
Britain still expects a confrontation in the security council. President
Bill Clinton is expected within the next day or so to meet his long-standing
commitment to Congress by tabling a UN resolution which would set a firm
spring deadline for the removal of the arms embargo.
London and Paris will not support such 'automaticity'. The two governments
will go no further than the existing wording of the contact group that
lifting the embargo may at some indeterminate stage be 'unavoidable'.
Mr Hurd's expectation is that the clash will be containable. If he goes
ahead Mr Clinton will have met his obligation to Congress by framing a
strong motion in support of the Bosnian Moslems. But, on British
calculations, the motion will not gain the necessary nine votes to get
through the security council.
The hope is that honour will thus be satisfied. And the contact group will
have six months grace to try to persuade, or rather coerce, the Bosnian
Serbs into a comprehensive settlement.
Viewed from the Foreign Office such a deal looks possible. Mr Hurd wants
other elements - including for example confirmation of the Serb-Croat border
and protection for the Serb enclaves in Croatia - drawn into the
negotiations. That would increase at least the number of cards on the table.
But to say a deal is probable would be to stretch the point. When pressed,
the British will admit that success or failure will depend not on any new
maps but on whether - and how quickly - President Miloslevic of Serbia wins
his power struggle with the Bosnian Serb leader Mr Radovan Karadzic.
The contact group has been told by the Russians that if the blockade imposed
by President Miloslevic was watertight, then the Bosnian Serbs' key supplies
would be exhausted within two months. But it is not watertight. All sorts of
people - including Moslems and Croatians - are willing apparently to supply
Mr Karadzic's army if the price is high enough.
Britain does not have the most creditable record over the break-up of the
former Yugoslavia. At the outset it was too eager to please Germany's
Chancellor Helmut Kohl by giving recognition to Croatia.
It insisted that sanctions were the best method against the Serbian forces
which overran a large part of Bosnia, but never did enough to ensure that
they worked. It was too dismissive of President Clinton's determination last
year to inject a moral dimension into the west's approach.
Now the unity of the western alliance depends on a Serbian president
defeating a Bosnian Serb warlord. If the latter holds on, the arms embargo
probably will be lifted next spring. In those circumstances the UN forces
will be withdrawn in a scramble. Bosnia, in the words of one member of the
British cabinet, will then go the way of Somalia. Everyone will blame
everyone else.
But Bosnia is not Somalia. History as well as geography tells us that. It is
in Europe's backyard. It is the fuse which could ignite wider conflagration
in the Balkans and explode the precarious attempts to build a post-Communist
international order.
So Mr Hurd is right to be preoccupied. And some time soon others at
Westminster may again start taking an interest in Bosnia's forgotten
conflict.
</TEXT>
<XX>
Countries:-
</XX>
<CN>GBZ  United Kingdom, EC.
    BAZ  Bosnia-Hercegovina, East Europe.
</CN>
