<HEADLINE>
FT  28 OCT 94 / Labour hit by frontbench shake-up row
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By KEVIN BROWN, Political Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
The last stage of Mr Tony Blair's shake-up of Labour's frontbench team is
being delayed by a row about his plans to restructure the whips' office.
Mr Blair was expected to complete his new line-up yesterday by announcing
the names of several appointments to the whips' office from the 1992 intake
of Labour MPs.
But the announcement had to be cancelled after Mr Don Dixon, the deputy
chief whip, complained that he had not been consulted.
Mr Dixon, who apparently discovered the proposed changes by accident, has
demanded time to consider Mr Blair's proposals and is not expected to
respond until Monday.
He said last night: 'I am pleased that the whips' office is getting more
recognition and more people. But I am not pleased about the fact that I was
not consulted about what is happening.'
Mr Dixon, the MP for Jarrow, is in a strong position to defy Mr Blair
because he is an elected official of the parliamentary Labour party. He
cannot be sacked or moved against his wishes. Regarded as a consummate
backstairs 'fixer', Mr Dixon has been elected deputy chief whip every year
since 1987, reflecting his popularity among Labour MPs.
The dispute is unlikely to prevent Mr Blair from pushing through the bulk of
his planned shake-up, which is intended to give the whips' office a fresh
role as a training ground for promising MPs.
However, a senior Labour MP said that the clash with Mr Dixon was likely to
be seen as further evidence of the inexperience of Mr Blair's close
advisers, many of whom have little experience of Westminster.
The Labour party's popularity has risen to its highest level ever, according
to an opinion poll published in The Times newspaper today.
The poll, conducted by MORI last weekend, puts Labour's rating at 57 per
cent, up from 54 per cent in late September. The Conservatives remain
unchanged at 25 per cent and the Liberal Democrats are down to 14 per cent
from a previous 17 per cent.
</TEXT>
<XX>
Countries:-
</XX>
<CN>GBZ  United Kingdom, EC.
