<HEADLINE>
FT  28 OCT 94 / Major and Blair clash on Aitken
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By KEVIN BROWN, Political Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Mr John Major and Mr Tony Blair clashed yesterday over allegations of
impropriety against Mr Jonathan Aitken, the Treasury chief secretary.
Amid rowdy Commons exchanges, Mr Major accused Mr Blair of 'descending into
the gutter of public life', as the Labour leader demanded a public hearing
of allegations against Mr Aitken and other ministers.
In the first serious Commons row since Mr Blair succeeded John Smith as
Labour leader, Mr Major bluntly refused to discuss the allegations and
accused opposition MPs of political grandstanding and peddling gossip.
The row blew up after Mr Aitken refused to duck questions about newspaper
allegations that he had lied to the cabinet secretary about reports that he
had paid only half his bill at the Paris Ritz, owned by Mr Mohamad Fayed,
the owner of Harrods.
Ignoring advice from Miss Betty Boothroyd, the speaker, that he need not
respond, Mr Aitken told Mr Gordon Brown, shadow chancellor, that he
completely denied the 'scurrilous accusations', printed in The Guardian.
'I hope this house, which is a very fair-minded place, will accept both my
assurance and the cabinet secretary's assurance, and put an end to the
hysterical atmosphere of sleaze journalism by The Guardian,' he said.
The claims of impropriety dominated prime minister's question time. Mr
Major, giving unequivocal support to Mr Aitken, refused to identify an
unnamed informant alleged to have made allegations on behalf of Mr Fayed.
As Tory MPs jeered, Mr Blair claimed Mr Neil Hamilton, the former corporate
affairs minister, had been sacked following 'unfounded' allegations but Mr
Aitken had been retained in spite of 'unsubstantiated' allegations. 'What is
the basis on which you decide to retain or dismiss your government ministers
 -the truth of the allegations or merely the number of them?' he demanded.
Mr Major said: 'I understood that when you became leader of the Labour party
we were going to see a new style in politics. I had not expected to see you
step down into the gutter of public life quite so soon.'
Mr Blair shot back: 'You will only get a grip on this problem when you
understand that there has to be a proper method of investigating the
allegations of Mr Al-Fayed in which the public has confidence, and that
means an open, full investigation in public view.'
Mr Major told Mr Blair: 'We now know where we are with you. We know
precisely what way you plan to play politics. You say you don't believe the
allegations are substantiated - yet still you are prepared in here to peddle
them.'
Rising for the third time - the first occasion on which he has done so since
becoming Labour leader - Mr Blair declared: 'It is not me that has dismissed
two of your ministers - it is you.'
He added: 'Nobody on this side is saying whether these allegations are true
or false, merely that they should be investigated. Why won't you allow that
to happen in public?'
Mr Major told him: 'You say the matters may not be true. They may be
unsubstantiated gossip and yet you want them peddled in public so that
people's reputations may be harmed.'
</TEXT>
