<HEADLINE>
FT  28 OCT 94 / Lloyds chief warns of large industry upheaval - Personnel
conference told of tough financial environment / Call to employ older people
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By RICHARD DONKIN
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Britain's financial services industry is facing an upheaval on the scale
that has been experienced by manufacturing industry, according to Sir Brian
Pitman, chief executive of Lloyds Bank.
Sir Brian said that although about 160,000 jobs had already been lost in
financial services in the past five years the competitive environment was
going to get tougher still.
If banks were to survive in the increasingly competitive market, he said,
they would no longer be able to give automatic pay rises.
He told the Institute of Personnel and Development annual conference in
Harrogate that further bank branch rationalisation that was likely to cause
unrest among bank employees. 'We have to be prepared in top management for
massive resistance in this change,' he said.
Sir Brian added: 'It is vital that top management is completely honest with
employees. You have to dampen down their expectations.'
He had told Lloyds Bank employees that a 1 per cent increase in their pay
was equivalent to 650 jobs.
Sir Brian said that the changes were being forced by Britain's low inflation
strategy leading to low demands for loans. Inflation would no longer bail
out poor advances on property, he said, meaning that banks would need to
manage their business more rigorously. Lloyds itself has closed 450 branches
in the past five years.
In a candid outline of the financial realities facing the banking sector he
said that banks' annual accounts would no longer be distorted by inflation,
giving them a deceptive gloss of health.
He said: 'Many people have grown fond of inflation. Annual pay rises and
rising house prices make people feel good, even if they mean little in
reality. In future the only good reason for a pay rise will be an increase
in a firm's productivity or the particular performance of an individual
team.'
Widespread overcapacity at a time of low growth, he said, might produce
unprecedented levels of competition in which only the most productive
companies were going to win. For bank employees it meant facing enormous
change.
'Having joined banking in the expectation of job security and steady career
progression, many are now faced with branch network rationalisation, job
losses and general uncertainty,' he added.
Sir Brian was criticised afterwards by the banking union Bifu.
Mr Ed Sweeny, deputy general secretary, said: 'He should stop, look and
listen to what his staff and customers are saying. The opprobrium heaped on
the banks during the last few years shows they are out of step with the
public.'
</TEXT>
<XX>
Countries:-
</XX>
<CN>GBZ  United Kingdom, EC.
</CN>
