<HEADLINE>
FT  28 OCT 94 / OECD ponders deal on top job
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By BERNARD SIMON and NANCY DUNNE
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   TORONTO, WASHINGTON
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
Members of the Paris-based Organisation for Economic Cooperation and
Development are considering a compromise in their long disagreement over a
new secretary-general.
Under the 'two-plus-five' deal, Mr Jean-Claude Paye of France who presently
holds the post would be reinstated for another two years. He would then be
succeeded by Canada's Mr Donald Johnston, a former cabinet minister, for a
full five-year term.
The Canadian foreign affairs department said yesterday that 'we don't have a
consensus yet. No deal has been done.' The appointment requires consensus
among all 25 members.
While it is clear that Paris and Ottawa favour the deal, the US has
indicated it is likely to oppose it. Washington is expected to hold firm to
its contention that new blood is needed in the OECD and that jobs in the
increasingly global trading system should no longer be based on regional
origin.
US officials believe the jobs call for 'higher profile people' who have easy
access to leaders and ministers.
The OECD job has become caught up in horse-trading over other top
international posts, notably head of the new World Trade Organisation,
successor to the General Agreement on Tariffs and Trade .
The three contenders for that post are South Korea's trade minister Mr Kim
Chul-su, Italy's former trade minister Mr Renato Ruggiero and Mexican
President Carlos Salinas de Gortari.
France and Canada have been discussing ways to break the deadlock over the
OECD post since Mr Andre Ouellet, Canada's foreign minister, visited Paris
earlier this month.
Mr Johnston, who works for a Montreal law firm, has been strongly backed by
the US and several other non-European members. They insist it is time for a
non-European to fill the post. But France, supported by most European
members, has until now refused to withdraw Mr Paye's candidacy for a third
five-year term.
</TEXT>
