<HEADLINE>
FT  28 OCT 94 / Zimbabwe may tell Oxfam to leave
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By MICHAEL HOLMAN, Africa Editor
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Oxfam, the UK charity, faces possible expulsion from Zimbabwe after an angry
government response to its criticisms of the country's health policy. In a
report* out this month, Oxfam accused the government of being partly to
blame for a reversal of post-independence improvements in health, by cutting
spending and imposing user fees.
In parliament, Mr John Nkomo, social welfare minister, condemned the study
as 'misleading, unscientific, and deliberately mischievous'. Its
'insinuations, distortions and deliberate falsification of figures are not
acceptable.'
Oxfam officials said last night they will be meeting the government in
Harare next week, but declined to comment on Mr Nkomo's apparent expulsion
threat. The report queries government claims that the country's structural
adjustment programme makes adequate provision for protecting the health of
the poor.
'Despite the mounting body of evidence showing a clear correlation between
user fees and worsening health indicators, the government of Zimbabwe
increased these fees and imposed more stringent conditions for their
collection in January 1994,' the study says.
Spending on health as a percentage of GDP has fallen to 2.7 per cent,
according to Oxfam, the lowest since independence in 1980. 'Under pressure
from the World Bank, the Zimbabwe government has increased expenditure since
1992,' says the report, noting 'a nominal increase in the 1992-93 budget
amounted to a decline in real terms of around 20 per cent.'
Government officials said Oxfam's local representatives had earlier been
summoned by Dr Timothy Stamps, health minister; he is understood to have
called for an apology and retraction.
There is an overwhelming case for withdrawing user fees, says Oxfam:
'Unfortunately, the Zimbabwe government's policy is pulling in precisely the
opposite direction, as witnessed by the sharp increase in user fees in
January 1994.'
Oxfam last night said it stood by the report. 'Our primary concern is relief
from poverty; we cannot be expected to turn a blind eye to policies which
result in the poor carrying the cost of macro-economic adjustments, however
necessary they may be,' Mr Stewart Wallis, overseas director, said.
Ironically, many of the findings are borne out by the government's own
research. *Paying for health: Poverty and Structural Adjustment in Zimbabwe,
by Jean Lennock. Oxfam, 274 Banbury Road, Oxford OX2 7DZ.
</TEXT>
