<HEADLINE>
FT  28 OCT 94 / Japan pension bill passed
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By WILLIAM DAWKINS
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   TOKYO
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
A bill to reform Japan's pensions system, to cope with the fast growing
number of elderly, was yesterday passed by the Diet's lower house. The
scheme will raise pension premiums and gradually increase eligible pension
age from 60 now to 65 in 2013. By then, one in four of the population will
be over 65, up from 12 per cent in 1990. Trade unions and pensioners'
lobbies had objected to the increase in pension premiums included in the
bill, but the government agreed to increase the pension premiums it
contributes from the national budget.
To ease the transition, pensioners beneath the new starting age will get a
partial hand-out, equal to roughly half a full pension. The basic monthly
pension will rise, from Y206,300 (Pounds 1,305) to Y214,300 next year, to be
funded by a rise in pension premiums from the present 14.5 per cent of
salary to 17.35 per cent. The bill gives the government a mandate to raise
premiums to a 29.6 per cent limit.
</TEXT>
