<HEADLINE>
FT  28 OCT 94 / Clinton supports Mideast bank
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JULIAN OZANNE
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   JERUSALEM
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
President Bill Clinton has committed the US to support the creation of a
Middle East development bank and announced fresh US aid, as part of an
increasing programme of financial support intended to underwrite
Arab-Israeli peace.
The US president yesterday also pledged to maintain the level of US economic
and military aid to Israel at Dollars 3bn (Pounds 1.8bn) a year, and
continue helping the Jewish state keep a strategic military edge over its
neighbours to 'build a peace that will bring with it the safety and security
Israel deserves'.
In a speech to the Jordanian parliament, Mr Clinton gave his
administration's first public backing to the creation of a regional
development bank to channel new investment to projects.
Mr Clinton pledged his government would take the lead in consultations with
regional and other governments to ensure that the development bank, which
will probably start with a capital base of Dollars 10bn, was properly
structured.
Israeli officials promoting the idea of a regional bank said yesterday Mr
Clinton's remarks would guarantee its creation and, in effect, over-ruled
objections raised by the US Treasury which had put forward an alternative
proposal for creation of a special 'window' in the World Bank for Middle
East regional projects.
Israel wants the US, Europe and Japan to provide 60 per cent of the capital
base of the regional development bank with proportional representation on
the board of directors and expects a US citizen to be the bank's first
president.
Mr Clinton also announced that his government's Overseas Private Investment
Corporation is establishing a Dollars 75m regional fund to encourage US
private-sector investment in joint projects between Israel and Jordan.
The US was committed to help Middle East peace makers 'write a real
practical future of hope', and ensure that peace delivered real economic
benefits to the citizens of the region, he added. 'If people do not feel
these benefits, if poverty persists, breeding despair and killing hope, then
the purveyors of fear will find fertile ground.'
An Israeli official said Mr Clinton's economic announcements showed the US
President understood the political rather than purely economic imperative
behind creating regional financial institutions.
Mr Clinton has underlined during his Middle East tour the vital economic
role the US is playing in the peace process. The US, Jordan and Israel have
set up an economic commission which has produced a plan to develop the
Israel-Jordan rift valley into a 'Valley of Peace' with projects in energy,
desalination, tourism, transport, environment and industry.
In Jordan, Mr Clinton promised 'actively to pursue practical means of
expanding trade and investment'. His administration would develop a
bilateral investment treaty, he declared.
Washington has already begun writing off Dollars 700m of debt owed by Jordan
to the US. Mr Clinton said in Amman he had pledged to forgive all Jordan's
US debts. He had called on Jordan's other creditors to follow his lead.
</TEXT>
