<HEADLINE>
FT  28 OCT 94 / Plan for Hadrian's Wall trail criticised
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By CHRIS TIGHE
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
The government has approved the Countryside Commission's controversial plan
for an 81-mile national trail for walkers alongside Hadrian's Wall, Chris
Tighe writes.
The commission believes the route, along the former northern boundary of the
Roman Empire from Wallsend in Tyne and Wear to Bowness on Solway in Cumbria,
could bring more than Pounds 1m a year into the local economy from visitors.
But yesterday Mr Peter Atkinson, Tory MP for Hexham, said that the trail
would bring chaos to land and livestock management and questioned how much
economic benefit it would generate. Archaeologist Professor Peter Fowler of
Newcastle University condemned the plan to create a 'pedestrian motorway'
through a designated World Heritage Site.
Announcing the decision, Mr Robert Atkins, environment minister, said the
government was satisfied that the commission had taken full account of the
implications of establishing the path alongside the world heritage site.
</TEXT>
