<HEADLINE>
FT  28 OCT 94 / International Company News: Salomon Bros in move to overhaul
its pay structure
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PATRICK HARVERSON
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   NEW YORK
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
Salomon Brothers, the Wall Street securities firm hit by heavy losses this
year, is to overhaul its system for compensating top executives in an
attempt to link pay more closely to performance.
The firm said the changes were also intended to make it easier to run its
various client-related businesses as a single global operation, and to
encourage better cost management.
Although the new system will only affect the firm's 125 or so highly-paid
managing directors in proprietary trading and client-driven businesses -
such as investment banking, securities sales and trading, and currencies -
their salaries and bonuses take up a significant share of Salomon's
compensation expenses.
While the bankers and traders in these core areas tend to be well-paid
whatever the circumstances, the revenues they generate can be volatile. This
often leaves the firm with a large wage bill, even when earnings are poor -
as has been the case this year, when Salomon in its first nine months lost
Dollars 547m on proprietary trading and other businesses. With the new pay
structure, Salomon's compensation expenses should move more in line with
performance.
Under the system, which will be introduced next year, managing directors in
the firm's client-driven businesses will receive a fixed minimum salary
equal to 35 per cent of this year's pay, plus 40 per cent of the earnings
their business generates in excess of an after-tax return to shareholders.
That return will initially be 7 per cent of equity capital, and will rise to
10 per cent over a two-year period.
Managing directors in Salomon's proprietary trading business, meanwhile,
will be paid from pooled deferred compensation accounts which accumulate pay
over a multi-year period. This could mean that traders may see their pay
from a good year subsequently reduced by losses incurred in a later, bad
year.
</TEXT>
<XX>
Companies:-
</XX>
<CO>Salomon Brothers Holdings International Inc.
</CO>
<XX>
Countries:-
</XX>
<CN>USZ  United States of America.
</CN>
<XX>
Industries:-
</XX>
<IN>P6211 Security Brokers and Dealers.
</IN>
<XX>
