<HEADLINE>
FT  28 OCT 94 / International Company News: Kimberly-Clark revises plans to
float pulp side
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By TONY JACKSON
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   NEW YORK
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
Kimberly-Clark, the Dallas-based maker of Kleenex tissues, is abruptly
revising its plans to float its North American pulp and newsprint
operations. The company said the sharp rise in pulp prices, unaccompanied by
a price increase for its finished products, made it in shareholders' best
interests to retain a majority stake for the time being.
Kimberly-Clark recently filed a preliminary prospectus in Canada for the 100
per cent flotation of a new company combining its pulp mill in Ontario and
its pulp and newsprint mill in Alaska.
Yesterday it said it would float only a third of the company, the earliest
date being the first quarter of 1995. Analysts had speculated that the
flotation could raise up to Dollars 950m. Kimberly-Clark is being advised by
Goldman Sachs and Salomon.
Kimberly-Clark had previously said it wanted to concentrate on its consumer
products business. It also needs cash to fund its expansion outside the US,
where its operations are still relatively small. Its bigger rival in the
tissue market, Scott Paper, said on Monday it would sell its pulp operations
as part of its own programme to focus on consumer products.
Last week Kimberly Clark's shares dropped almost 9 per cent in response to
third-quarter figures showing it was being hit hard by the cost of its
European expansion.
</TEXT>
