<HEADLINE>
FT  28 OCT 94 / International Company News: Benetton team wins GS-Autogrill
bidding
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ROBERT GRAHAM
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   ROME
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
An Italo-Swiss consortium, headed by Benetton, last night came away with the
winning bid for GS-Autogrill, the last part of the SME foodstuffs group to
be privatised.
The winning consortium consists of Edizione Holding, the Benetton family's
financial holding, plus the Swiss hotel and restaurant group, the Del
Vecchio group, and Crediop, the financial institution.
IRI, the state holding company, owns 62 per cent of SME. The bid was for 32
per cent of its stock, with the obligation to make a similarly priced offer
for at least a further 20 per cent held by minority shareholders. The winner
also then must buy up the remaining IRI shares.
No value was put on the deal but analysts estimate Autogrill is worth
L2,000bn (Dollars 1.31bn). IRI said it found the Benetton group's offer the
best and would present the decision to a shareholders' meeting on November
4.
The Benetton bid beat another offer on the table, from a Italian group
comprising Rinascente, the quoted Italian retail group, Ferrero, the
confectionery company and Fincomit, the merchant banking arm of Banca
Commerciale Italiana.
SME's shares were up 0.7 per cent at L4,086 yesterday ahead of the decision.
In the first half of this year SME's consolidated turnover was L2,026bn, up
4.7 per cent on the same period in 1993. Of this, L1,370bn came from the
stores side and L625bn from the restaurant business.
The award concludes a long and painful attempt by IRI to find a buyer for
SME's stores and motorway restaurant division. It also marks the end of the
messy break-up of SME. The state-run group was split into three divisions to
ease its privatisation in early 1993 - Italgel (frozen foods), Cirio Bertoli
De Rica (oil, canned goods, milk) and GS-Autogrill.
GS-Autogrill was first put out to private tender in September 1993 but the
sale was dropped because the offers were considered unsatisfactory.
A second attempt to sell was initiated in April this year, but in September
the process was revoked and new bids sought.
</TEXT>
<XX>
Companies:-
</XX>
<CO>Societa Generale Supermercati.
    Autogrill.
    SME International.
