<HEADLINE>
FT  28 OCT 94 / Reforms for The Law Commission
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
The Law Commission yesterday called for reforms to cut delays in handling
legal challenges to government decisions.
Judicial review applications have risen from 160 in 1974 to 1,500 by 1987
and almost 2,900 last year. The rise has continued this year, with 1,851
applications in the first seven months compared with 1,728 in the same
period of last year.
The government's law reform body said that if delays in hearing legal
challenges were to be reduced procedures for judicial review would have to
be streamlined.
It is proposing several changes to make procedures easier for applicants.
The terms and remedies available will be changed to make their function and
purpose more easily understood.
The commission also recommends that courts hearing public law cases should
have the power to order restitution where organisations or individuals have
wrongly been required to pay out money.
It says rules on time limits, the availability of interim remedies pending a
full hearing - in particular against ministers and central government
departments - and rules on appeals all need clarifying and updating.
Administrative Law: Judicial Review and Statutory Appeals. HMSO. Pounds
18.75.
</TEXT>
<XX>
