<HEADLINE>
FT  28 OCT 94 / Burns criticised on Treasury cuts
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JAMES BLITZ
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Sir Terry Burns, the perma-nent secretary of the Treasury, was last night
attacked for failing to consult opposition parties over cuts in his
department's manpower.
Mr Peter Mandelson, the Labour MP for Hartlepool who was this week tipped
for a key job in the Labour whips' office, accused Sir Terry of 'a
dereliction of duty' by not informing the Labour party about drastic
reductions in the number of Treasury civil servants.
In an adjournment debate on the civil service, Mr Mandelson said Sir Terry
needed to ensure that the Treasury machine remained fully operative for
subsequent administrations.
He insisted that Sir Terry should hold talks with Mr Gordon Brown, shadow
chancellor, well before the next general election to be fully briefed on the
party's economic plans.
'Upon a change of government, the Treasury will need to shift radically and
quickly to new priorities and ways of working,' he said. 'There wouldn't be
time to waste.'
Earlier this month Sir Terry announced a shake up of its structure, which
will involve the loss of about one in four senior staff.
Seventeen Labour MPs yesterday submitted an early-day motion calling for the
government to carry out a fundamental review of the beleaguered Child
Support Agency.
As concern grows about the agency's record in its first year in operation,
the MPs claimed that the organisation aimed to 'support the Treasury rather
than the child'.
</TEXT>
