<HEADLINE>
FT  28 OCT 94 / More armour in Middle East
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By REUTER
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   WASHINGTON
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
Qatar and Kuwait have agreed to provide bases for additional US armour and
attack jets in a Gulf build-up to prepare for any new military threat from
Iraq, the US Defence Department said yesterday.
Qatar will accept the positioning of tanks and supplies for use by a brigade
of over 2,000 US troops should the need arise again to send American
soldiers to the Gulf. A squadron of about 24 A-10 attack jets, slow flying
and heavily armed aircraft designed to smash tanks, will also be sent to
Kuwait. Defence officials said they considered the agreement with Qatar a
breakthrough in the Pentagon's push to position more heavy armour in the
region to meet any potential Iraqi threat or build-up.
Qatar was used as a base for F-16s during the 1991 Gulf War. 'Qatar has
allowed us to put in a full brigade's worth of equipment,' the Pentagon
said. 'A squadron of A-10s will be deployed in Kuwait.' The US is now
seeking to store enough armour on the ground in the Gulf region for three
brigades representing about a division of 10,000 troops.
</TEXT>
