<HEADLINE>
FT  27 OCT 94 / Tapie in courtroom battle
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ANDREW JACK
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   PARIS
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
Mr Bernard Tapie, the controversial French businessman and politician,
yesterday renewed his legal battle against Credit Lyonnais, the troubled
state-owned bank to which he owes an estimated FFr1.2bn (Pounds 140m). In a
packed courtroom of the Tribunal de Grande Instance in Paris, Mr Tapie's
lawyers argued that Credit Lyonnais should be forced to stick by the terms
of a deal it reached with him in March this year to repay his loans over
five years. Credit Lyonnais argues the agreement is void because he did not
supply the necessary expert opinions in time to support the high value he
claimed for the assets against which the accord was secured. The bank
already has custody of many of Mr Tapie's assets, including shares, his
furniture collection, his yacht and his house in Paris. Valuations suggest
they may be worth substantially less than his debts, with one putting them
at FFr300m. Judgment is expected in several weeks.
</TEXT>
