<HEADLINE>
FT  27 OCT 94 / International Company News: Top analyst loses job at Lehman
Brothers
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PATRICK HARVERSON
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   NEW YORK
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
Ms Elaine Garzarelli, the Wall Street analyst who earned fame and fortune
after predicting the 1987 market crash, lost her job yesterday when Lehman
Brothers decided it could no longer afford her million-dollar salary.
The investment bank issued a terse statement saying that the 46-year old
analyst, who was director of sector analysis, had left to 'pursue other
opportunities'. However, sources close to Lehman said the bank had conducted
a review of Ms Garzarelli's job and concluded it was no longer
cost-effective to keep her.
Ms Garzarelli's departure from Lehman shocked Wall Street. There were no
indications that she had lost favour (although she recently issued a market
forecast that contradicted advice from Lehman's chief investment strategist)
and she remained highly regarded in the financial community.
Ms Garzarelli's views were not just followed on Wall Street. She was
familiar to millions of individual American investors through her many
television appearances, and was so well-known that she appeared in
advertisements last year for a brand of tights.
However, Ms Garzarelli was becoming a luxury Lehman could no longer afford.
In the latest quarter, earnings at the investment bank - which was spun off
from American Express in a stock market flotation last year - plunged 89 per
cent to Dollars 11m. It has since been cutting its payroll as part of a
cost-reduction strategy.
Although she has suffered some setbacks - her attempt to run an investment
fund was conspicuously unsuccessful - Ms Garzarelli is likely to receive
plenty of job offers.
Ms Joan Zimmerman of the Wall Street executive recruitment firm GZ Stephens
said: 'She has a tremendously strong public persona, and that persona can
translate into an ability to bring money into any organisation.'
</TEXT>
