<HEADLINE>
FT  27 OCT 94 / International Company News: DuPont chemical division jumps
97% in third term
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By TONY JACKSON
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   NEW YORK
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
DuPont of the US, the world's largest chemical company, confirmed the
strength of the cyclical upswing in its industry with a 97 per cent jump in
third-quarter net earnings from its chemical operations overall.
This was partly offset by a 5 per cent drop in earnings from its Conoco oil
subsidiary. However, net earnings before extraordinary items were up 86 per
cent at Dollars 680m.
The rise in chemical profits was driven by higher volumes and by reduced
fixed costs, the company said, with the two factors contributing equally.
However, selling prices had remained flat in spite of sharp volume
increases.
The rise in group earnings was helped by a sharp turnround in DuPont's
diversified businesses division, where profits jumped to Dollars 135m from
Dollars 6m. The company said this was due to the recovery in its coal mining
business, hit by strikes last year, and to better profits in agrochemicals
and medical products.
In DuPont's own narrowly defined chemicals division, earnings were up 126
per cent at Dollars 104m. Volume was up 9 per cent, made up of a 4 per cent
rise in the US and a 27 per cent rise in the rest of the world. Prices were
up 2 per cent.
In the polymers division, earnings were up 149 per cent at Dollars 177m.
Volume was up 15 per cent, made up of 11 per cent in the US and 21 per cent
elsewhere. Prices were 1 per cent lower. Earnings in the fibres division
were up 50 per cent at Dollars 164m. Volume was 6 per cent higher and prices
were static.
Oil earnings were down 5 per cent overall at Dollars 172m, made up of a 23
per cent drop in upstream earnings and a 22 per cent rise in downstream.
Upstream operations were hit by lower gas volume, lower crude oil volume in
the US and higher exploration costs. Downstream earnings were helped by
higher US margins in refined products and more turnover at refineries.
DuPont said that while chemicals prices were flat year on year, they were up
modestly from their low point in the second quarter.
</TEXT>
<XX>
