<HEADLINE>
FT  27 OCT 94 / Sweden's Securum to seek Pounds 1.73bn
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By CHRISTOPHER BROWN-HUMES
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   STOCKHOLM
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
Securum, the Swedish state-owned company set up to liquidate Nordbanken's
bad loans, yesterday launched a SKr20bn (Pounds 1.73bn) refinancing in the
international capital markets in one of the country's biggest non-government
debt issues.
The funds will be used to repay most of the loans Securum received from
Nordbanken, the biggest casualty of Sweden's banking crisis, when it took
over SKr67bn worth of sour credits at the start of 1993.
The move allows Securum to widen its borrowing base and assists government
efforts to privatise Nordbanken by reducing the bank's uncomfortably large
exposure to a single client. Privatisation is expected to take place next
year, but awaits a formal go-ahead from the new Social Democratic
government.
Mr Anders Nyren, Securum's chief financial officer, said the company wanted
to 'position itself in the international markets for future business
transactions.' He stressed there would only be 'a very marginal' increase in
the company's funding costs, even though the loans from Nordbanken were
granted on a 'cost of funds' basis.
Nordbanken will remain Securum's single largest creditor, but outstanding
loans are expected to fall to between SKr5bn and SKr10bn from nearly
SKr23bn.
There are two tranches, both backed by the Swedish government. Under the
international one, Chemical Bank and Enskilda Corporate will arrange a
Dollars 1.4bn (Pounds 857m) five-year syndicated term loan. Terms will be
Libor plus 25 basis points. Enskilda Corporate and Nordbanken will arrange a
SKr10bn domestic financing programme to run over 10 years, to be split
between a SKr5bn subordinated term loan and a SKr5bn subordinated private
placement.
Securum made a SKr6.3bn profit in the first six months of 1994. It has moved
from being a finance company to an investment and property holding group. It
has a SKr21bn European asset portfolio outside Sweden and believes its
development will benefit from contacts with leading international banks. It
plans to list many of its industrial and property operations. The aim is to
return at least SKr10bn of its SKr24bn initial equity to the state by the
time its assets are liquidated.
</TEXT>
