<HEADLINE>
FT  27 OCT 94 / Arts: Today's Television
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By CHRISTOPHER DUNKLEY
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
As part of BBC2's 'Bard On The Box' season, Michael Bogdanov organises
Shakespeare On The Estate, an exercise which sounds perilously like slumming
by Islington trendies, but we shall see. It seems that on the Ladywood
estate in Birmingham Bogdanov visits pubs, youth groups and young mothers'
centres, and ends up using a tower-block balcony for the famous Romeo and
Juliet scene (9.00). It would be hard to dream up a madder way of looking
after our health than requiring completely inexperienced doctors in their
mid-20s to work more than 100 hours a week, providing emergency cover
throughout a general hospital, including the casualty department, in shifts
lasting 24 or even 48 hours. Yet that is what happens. Inside Story watches
two junior doctors at the Middlesex/UCH complex in London (10.00 BBC1). We
know that a vestry is a place where a clergyman may keep or even change his
clothes, but is it really the place for a bishop to investigate the inside
of his secretary's blouse? That is what was happening in last week's
late-night soap, Revelations (10.40 ITV).
</TEXT>
