<HEADLINE>
FT  27 OCT 94 / The Local Government Commission: Cost of Pounds 8m council
study angers critics / A look at whether spending on the review paid off
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JOHN AUTHERS
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Sir John Banham said yesterday that the Local Government Commission's Pounds
8m budget for this year was 'money well spent'. Many disagree with him.
Labour yesterday described the commission's review of local authority
structure as 'a waste of time and money', while Professor Michael Clarke of
Birmingham University's Institute of Local Government Studies said the
'entire remit the commission was given was flawed'.
Sir John argued that by consulting widely and expensively - with
questionnaires sent to every household in the areas for which proposals were
announced yesterday - the commission had avoided what could have been
'unpopular expensive mistakes' in six counties.
'If we had pressed ahead with our recommendations without listening to local
people we would be recommending transitional costs of the order of Pounds
135m,' he said.
Sir John added that the commission's Pounds 8m budget was spread over 32
counties, so reviewing each had cost only about Pounds 250,000. This was
'minuscule' compared with the overall annual English local government budget
of about Pounds 40bn.
Prof Clarke described this argument as 'incredible' and said it would have
been better not to spend any money at all.
Critics of the review also pointed out that Mr John Gummer, the environment
secretary, last year proposed to abandon the review except in counties where
a sizeable proportion of local residents signed petitions asking for change.
This could have averted all expenditure by the commission in counties such
as Oxfordshire, where substantial opposition to change was found.
The costs of the review go beyond the commission's own budget. According to
Prof Clarke, long-term planning in the shire counties and districts had been
virtually shelved for the last two years as local authorities devoted all
their energies to the review.
The financial cost in terms of lost opportunities was 'if not incalculable,
then certainly enormous', he said. Councils had been attempting to introduce
the council tax and prepare for compulsory competitive tendering of
white-collar services.
Officials of the national local authority associations say the review has
taken up 'at least 95 per cent' of their time, while work on other topics
has been abandoned.
Further, both districts and counties have launched expensive publicity
campaigns of their own. Districts claim that county councils such as Essex
and Nottinghamshire spent as much as Pounds 150,000 on publicity campaigns
about the review, and have made official complaints to the Audit Commission,
the watchdog for local government expenditure.
Sir John's commission has also complained about districts' expenditure. For
example, in Derbyshire, one of the first counties to be reviewed, all the
districts hired consultants to advise on their public relations strategy in
dealing with the review, while all the district councils in Surrey hired
CSL, the managed services division of Touche Ross, to help prepare their
submission on the review.
Several counties recommended for abolition earlier in the process have
sought judicial review of the decisions, at a cost of around Pounds 100,000
each. The High Court has rejected every attempt so far to overturn the
commission's recommendations, but the attempts continue. Humberside said
yesterday that it would seek judicial review of Mr Gummer's announcement
that it should be abolished.
In those areas where Sir John recommended change yesterday, he believes
there will be a big bill, which must eventually be paid by local council-tax
payers. In total, he estimates the cost of reorganising Bedfordshire,
Buckinghamshire and Hampshire at between Pounds 27m and Pounds 35m. Also,
reorganisation will create additional annual costs of between Pounds 2m and
Pounds 12m.
Sir John said: 'Any reorganisation costs more and delivers less than its
proponents suggest.' Prof Clarke agreed, saying the 'overwhelming' evidence
from previous reorganisations was that setting up new authorities would
cause high transitional costs which could not be recovered by later annual
savings.
Business leaders share these concerns. Mr Howard Davies, director-general of
the Confederation of British Industry, described the reorganisation as an
'expensive' hobby for the government.
But the cross-party Association of District Councils refuses to slacken its
own lobbying effort, and has asked for an 'urgent' meeting with the prime
minister.
The association wants the government to reject the commission's proposals.
That would mean requiring the commission to start its review again from
scratch. Yesterday, there was little or no sign of political support for
such a move.
</TEXT>
