<HEADLINE>
FT  27 OCT 94 / The Local Government Commission: Plans to axe six counties
abandoned
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JOHN AUTHERS
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Banham signals rejection of unitary authorities; Labour says government
policy in turmoil
Sir John Banham, chairman of the Local Government Commission, yesterday
announced that plans to abolish six county councils - Cambridgeshire,
Cheshire, Cumbria, Kent, Lancashire and Oxfordshire - had been abandoned.
The announcement signals a decisive rejection of the government's original
preference that county councils should be replaced by unitary authorities
combining the powers of counties and districts in all bar 'exceptional'
circumstances.
Of the 17 counties for which proposals have been announced so far, 10 will
keep the two-tier system at least in part. Proposals for the other shire
counties will be given to the government by the end of the year, and few are
likely to involve a unitary structure.
Sir John's proposals followed the decision of Mr John Gummer, the
environment secretary, not to proceed with plans to restructure Somerset and
North Yorkshire. Mr Gummer has the power to ask the commission to reconsider
its proposals, but seems unlikely to use it.
Opposition politicians said the government's policy was in chaos. Mr Frank
Dobson, shadow environment secretary, said: 'The present position is yet
another monument to government incompetence. Turmoil and trouble, all for
nothing - a useless distraction.'
The commission has proposed a change to the structure of Hampshire, with
Portsmouth, Southampton and the New Forest district councils all given
unitary status on their current boundaries. The proposals for the two cities
were widely predicted, but the New Forest unitary was a surprise.
Sir John said the commission's opinion survey in the area had shown
overwhelming support for a unitary authority independent of Hampshire, with
60 per cent of residents in favour of this option.
In Buckinghamshire and Bedfordshire, Sir John recommended more radical
change - the abolition of both county councils and unitary status for most
of the lower-tier district councils on their current boundaries.
Milton Keynes, Aylesbury Vale and Wycombe in Bucks will all be unitary, with
a new merged South Buckinghamshire authority created by linking the existing
Chiltern and South Bucks councils.
Mr David Rendel, Liberal Democrat local government spokesman, said this
would mean abolishing the one county council still controlled by the
Conservatives after their bad showing in last year's local elections.
Bedfordshire will be split into three unitaries, rather than the two
originally recommended, with unitary status for Luton and Bedford.
                           *      *      *
 -----------------------------------------------------------------------
1991:          Government raises prospect of ending traditional two-tier
               system in which large county councils and smaller
               district councils hold different powers over the same
               areas
 -----------------------------------------------------------------------
May 1993:      Review commission's first recommendations involve
               abolishing several county councils
 -----------------------------------------------------------------------
July 1993:     John Major vetoes proposal by environment minister
               John Gummer to abandon the review for all counties and
               send the commission only to counties where a majority
               request it
 -----------------------------------------------------------------------
Oct 1993:      Gummer announces changed guidance to the commission:
               retaining existing two-tier administration is now
               to be the 'exception'
 -----------------------------------------------------------------------
Jan 1994:      Lancashire county council, threatened with abolition,
               wins court judgment that Gummer's 'exception' rule is
               unlawful
 -----------------------------------------------------------------------
Summer 1994:   Commission suggests abolishing several county councils
               and handing their powers to enlarged districy authorties;
               launches local 'advisory referenda'
 -----------------------------------------------------------------------
October 1994:  Referenda show widespread opposition to administration
               by enlarged district councils
 -----------------------------------------------------------------------
