<HEADLINE>
FT  27 OCT 94 / Royal Commission on the Environment: Pollution report poses
stiff challenge for ministers
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DAVID LASCELLES, Resources Editor
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Sir John Houghton, chairman of the Royal Commission on Environmental
Pollution, was keen to stress yesterday that his report was in tune with the
government's desire for a sustainable transport policy.
On the face of it, that is true. Earlier this year Mr John Major launched a
weighty document on sustainable development which spoke of the need 'to
strike the right balance between the ability of transport to serve economic
development and the ability to protect the environment and sustain future
quality of life'.
But the government has so far done little to put that policy into practice.
Cynics would even say that those fine words bear little relation to actual
policy, which is dominated by favouritism for the car and a desire to
shuffle off the problems of public transport by privatising it.
Yesterday's report is therefore a challenge to ministers to match words with
deeds. But it goes further than that by urging a fundamental reshaping of
the economics of transport to bring out its true costs.
Professor Richard Macrory, a commission member and a barrister, described
the report as 'a last chance' for the Department of Transport to become 'a
real transport department' rather than just a roads department. 'Many people
in evidence to us said the department was biased towards roads. We feel that
is correct.'
Small surprise, therefore, that ministers gave the report a guarded welcome
yesterday. It puts pressure on the government on several fronts.
One is taxation. Although Mr Kenneth Clarke, the chancellor, is committed to
raising the price of vehicle fuel by 5 per cent a year, the commission wants
that rate to be doubled.
The Treasury would no doubt welcome an opportunity to raise more revenue.
But the closer the government moves to a general election, the less likely
such a measure looks, particularly since the commission admits: 'We
recognise that the policies we recommend will impose costs on the present
generation.' Though it adds they could be offset by cuts in other taxes.
Another is the balance between public and private transport. Although the
government is showing signs of soft-pedalling its roads programme, it has
done little to compensate by boosting public transport. The commission does
not challenge the wisdom of privatising trains and buses, but it urges a
heavy commitment of public funds to develop public transport.
Interestingly, it expresses reservations about one of the few measures the
government is proposing to jack up the cost of motoring: motorway tolls.
Commission members fear this will only divert heavy traffic to smaller roads
less capable of handling it.
A further challenge raised by the report is its implication that road travel
is far too cheap. Could the economy sustain a sharp increase in transport
costs? What would happen to industry if some of the commission's
recommendations on freight transport were adopted - for example, halting the
strengthening of road bridges and banning big lorries from city centres?
The government has been reluctant to land industry with environmental
charges for fear of damaging competitiveness, and it has been vociferous in
its opposition to Brussels' plans for a carbon tax.
Even so, Sir Geoffrey Allen, one of the few industrialists on the
commission, believes industry can cope. 'There's lots of flexibility in the
system,' he said yesterday. 'Companies will react and find other ways of
moving their goods.'
The report also anticipates objections from the industrial lobby that its
recommendations would damage the vehicle manufacturing and road building
industries.
'There will be alternative work in providing improved infrastructure for
public transport, such as new light rail systems or upgraded railway lines,'
it says. For the automobile and freight industries, the challenge lies in
developing new eco-friendly vehicles.
On the planning front, the commission believes greater account should be
taken of environmental considerations when planning transport routes.
The report pointedly contains a colour picture of Twyford Down, an area of
outstanding natural beauty which the Department of Transport authorised in
1991 to be destroyed in order to extend the M3. Although there have been
signs of a more balanced approach since then, the government is not known
for its care of the natural environment.
One respect in which the government will welcome the report is that it lends
support to its efforts to curb atmospheric pollution.
At the 1992 Rio Earth Summit, the UK signed a treaty committing it to try to
bring carbon dioxide emissions back to 1990 levels by the year 2000. A big
contribution to achieving this goal will have to come from transport.
Therefore any recommendations to curb vehicle exhaust will be good news, at
least for Mr John Gummer, the environment secretary.
The commission is aware that its recommendations will be tough for the
government, and will create divisions among departments, for example between
environment and trade and industry over raising the cost of transport for
industry. But, as the report points out, policymakers failed to bite the
bullet when these issues arose 20 years ago.
It says: 'It is a truly daunting prospect that, if the present opportunity
were also to be lost, our successors would again be debating the increasing
effects of road transport on the environment in the 2010s, following 20 more
years of environmental deterioration.'
Transport and the Environment. Command number 2674. HMSO. Pounds 25.60.
</TEXT>
