<HEADLINE>
FT  27 OCT 94 / Royal Commission on the Environment: Business slams heavy
burden
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By CHARLES BATCHELOR, Transport Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Business and motoring organisations criticised the report for suggesting
measures which would place too heavy a burden on drivers and the haulage
industry.
The Confederation of British Industry warned that the proposal to raise fuel
duty and cut road spending would do little to reduce road congestion - but
would damage British competitiveness.
The confederation said the present roads programme had to be maintained if
the UK was to overcome years of neglect and catch up with its competitors
elsewhere in Europe.
'The fear is that the short-sharp-shock treatment proposed by the commission
will make road transport very expensive but offer little in terms of
realistic alternative ways for individuals to travel and for businesses to
transport their goods and services,' said Mr Howard Davies, CBI
director-general.
The Freight Transport Association, which represents 12,000 hauliers and
shippers, described the report as 'unrealistic and potentially damaging to
the economy'. Increasing fuel duty would increase inflation instead of
transferring freight to rail, it said.
A high-quality environment depended on a strong, competitive economy which
would not be achieved by pricing traffic off the roads, warned the British
Roads Federation, which represents many companies that ship goods by road.
It called for higher investment to remove through traffic from towns and
villages.
The Automobile Association said private motorists were being faced with
penalties to force them to leave their cars 'for non-existent or inadequate
alternatives'. It called for improvements to public transport before
motorists could be expected to leave their cars behind. Four out of five
drivers would continue to use their cars even if the price of petrol were
doubled over the next 10 years, an AA survey has showed.
The Royal Automobile Club said the fuel-price mechanism was 'a crude, cruel
and ineffective lever' which would hit the elderly, the disabled, women, and
people living in the country the hardest.
However, Transport 2000, a campaign group in favour of public transport,
backed the report. It called on the government to use the Budget to make the
switch from roads spending to devoting resources to trains, buses, cycling
and traffic-calming measures.
</TEXT>
