<HEADLINE>
FT  27 OCT 94 / Royal Commission on the Environment: Green groups hail hope
of victory
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DAVID LASCELLES
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
The report was enthusiastically welcomed by environmental groups, which saw
it as potentially a breakthrough in their campaign for greener transport
policies.
Greenpeace described it as 'a watershed in the battle against subsidised
pollution', and the Council for the Protection of Rural England said the
report showed 'vision'.
The report was also welcomed by campaigners for cleaner air and a reduction
in asthma, now widely linked to transport pollution.
After some notorious battles over new road schemes, the report's emphasis on
the 'best practicable environmental option' will encourage green groups to
take a more aggressive stance on future plans.
The Royal Society for the Protection of Birds said that 160 sites of special
scientific interest were directly at risk from the roads programme, and that
wildlife was suffering from polluting emissions.
The environmental lobby will be pressing for action to curb the roads
programme; greater taxation to make road transport bear the full costs of
the environmental damage it causes; and promotion of alternative means of
transport, including new technology; and better facilities for cyclists and
pedestrians.
</TEXT>
