<HEADLINE>
FT  27 OCT 94 / Medical insurance tax relief costs soar
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DAVID OWEN
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
The cost to the government of giving tax relief on private medical insurance
for the over-60s is still rising rapidly in spite of moves in last year's
Budget to limit the rate of the relief to 25 per cent.
A written answer last week by Sir George Young, financial secretary to the
Treasury, put the cost of the relief in 1994-95 at Pounds 95m - up from
Pounds 80m in 1993-94. Last November, the Inland Revenue said the cost in
1994-95 was expected to be 'around Pounds 85m'. The Revenue yesterday said
that the premiums charged by private-sector insurers had gone up much more
than expected.
Sir George's answer - in response to a written question by Mr Hugh Bayley,
Labour MP for York - also revealed that the annual cost of providing the
relief has more than doubled since its introduction in April 1990.
</TEXT>
