<HEADLINE>
FT  27 OCT 94 / Allies of Blair win jobs in reshuffle
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DAVID OWEN
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Mr Tony Blair yesterday tightened his grip on Labour's economic strategy
with an extensive shake-up of the party's frontbench team. The move puts
several younger allies who last week failed to be elected to the shadow
cabinet in key positions.
The Labour leader underlined his determination to put the main economic
departments firmly in the hands of the party's modernising wing by
appointing Mr Brian Wilson and Ms Hilary Armstrong to prominent posts in the
trade and industry and Treasury teams respectively.
Mr Wilson augmented his reputation with his skilful harrying of the
government as shadow transport spokesman during the railway privatisation
bill. Ms Armstrong was a loyal aide to John Smith, the former Labour leader.
Mr Alistair Darling, another close ally of Mr Blair, will continue in his
role as the party's City spokesman, with Mr Alun Michael continuing to
support Mr Jack Straw in home affairs.
This leaves Ms Dawn Primarolo as the only 'traditionalist' member of Mr
Gordon Brown's shadow Treasury team. Mr Andrew Smith, another moderniser,
was confirmed as shadow chief secretary to the Treasury some days ago.
Mr Derek Fatchett, a leading traditionalist, was moved from trade and
industry to defence.
Mr Blair was expected today to signal his intention of reshaping the Labour
whip's office as the principal training ground for the party's stars of the
future. Mr Peter Mandelson, the party's former communications director, was
among a number of members of Labour's 1992 Commons intake being tipped for a
job there as part of the new strategy.
There were several prominent jobs for women in the new line-up. Ms Ann Clwyd
was appointed to back up Mr John Prescott, deputy leader, as well as moving
to Mr Robin Cook's frontbench foreign affairs team where she joins Ms Joyce
Quin. Ms Joan Ruddock will be the party's spokeswoman on environmental
protection. Ms Llin Golding will speak on children and families.
In employment, Mr Kevin Barron, an ex-aide to Mr Neil Kinnock, the former
Labour leader, will support Ms Harriet Harman along with Mr Ian McCartney, a
traditionalist.
Mr Kevin McNamara, previously Northern Ireland spokesman, moves to the civil
service portfolio. Mr George Foulkes, who resigned as defence spokesman a
year ago before he was fined for assaulting a police constable, returns as
overseas development spokesman. The home affairs team is completed by Mr
George Howarth, noted for his research into quangos, and Mr Kim Howells. Mr
David Blunkett will be supported in education by Mr Bryan Davies and Mr
Peter Kilfoyle, an unsuccessful challenger as chief whip. Mr Nick Brown
joins Mrs Margaret Beckett at health.
</TEXT>
