<HEADLINE>
FT  27 OCT 94 / Quality standard rigidity rapped
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By RICHARD GOURLAY
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
The BS5750 quality assurance standard is unsuitable for the smallest
companies, the Small Business Research Trust warned yesterday.
In a report the group says the standard is too costly, rigid and formal for
smaller companies which often rely on the 'hands-on approach' of
owner-managers.
There was no evidence that informal quality systems, based on the personal
involvement of business owners and employees with detailed knowledge of
customer requirements, were inferior to more formal systems such as BS5750
accreditation, the report says.
The report is based on responses from more than 4,000 smaller companies and
was sponsored by the Department of Trade and Industry, the British Standards
Institution and National Westminster Bank.
It is one of the most comprehensive inquiries into the relevence to small
businesses of a standard that the institution says was 'written by big
business for big business'.
The survey found that BS5750 - or BS EN ISO 9000, as it is now called after
its European Union counterpart - was widely seen as a useful marketing tool.
'Users derived significant benefits, notably relating to marketing and
competitive issues rather than internal operational efficiency', the report
says.
Mr Francis Chittenden of Manchester Business School's business development
unit, co-author of the report, said it showed that BS5750 would be relevant
to some small companies and not others.
Small Businesses &amp; BS5750. Small Business Research Trust, School of
Management, Open University, Walton Hall, Milton Keynes, MK7 6AA. Pounds 10.
</TEXT>
