<HEADLINE>
FT  27 OCT 94 / Personnel directors lose on pay
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By RICHARD DONKIN, Labour Staff
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Personnel directors are paid an average of almost 10 per cent less than
other types of director, a report published today has found.
The report on personnel management pay, published by the Reward Group in
association with the Institute of Personnel and Development, says that,
overall, personnel staff received a median across-the-board pay rise of 3
per cent in the past 12 months.
Personnel directors earn Pounds 45,000 a year on average, says Reward,
compared with Pounds 49,920 for all other types of director. Most middle and
senior ranking personnel managers below the level of director, however, are
ahead of their management colleagues. A senior personnel manager could
expect to earn Pounds 36,500 a year on average against Pounds 34,736 for
other managers at an equivalent level.
The pay of women personnel officers trails that of men. The proportion of
women in top personnel jobs, however, is growing. Just over a quarter of
personnel directors in the survey were women, compared with just over a
fifth in the previous two years.
The report found a high level of job satisfaction in personnel departments
although overall, compared with last year, respondents consider they have
fewer job prospects.
The Institute of Personnel and Development is preparing a bid for royal
charter status, Mr Geoff Armstrong, its director general, said yesterday.
The 72,000-strong institute was formed this year by a merger between the
Institute of Personnel Management and the Institute of Training and
Development.
Personnel Rewards. Reward Group, Diamond Way, Stone Business Park,
Staffordshire ST15 OSD. Pounds 230.
</TEXT>
