<HEADLINE>
FT  27 OCT 94 / Accountants warned on ties to Tories
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JIM KELLY, Accountancy Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
The accountancy profession should distance itself from the Conservative
party and the interests of the big firms, one of the six leading trade
bodies has urged.
The deputy chief executive of Cipfa, the public services accountancy
institute, warned in a provocative speech that the profession was seen by
many as 'overly political'.
Mr Richard Morris said: 'The profession has a considerable number of
Conservative MPs, tends to act through Conservative spokesmen, but not
always, and this encourages its perception as being part of the
establishment.'
The speech acknowledges that efforts by the six professional bodies to agree
reforms to the profession through the Bishop committee have 'stalled'.
Coupled with recent moves by other professional bodies, the speech indicates
a widespread belief that the committee is unable to break the deadlock over
institutional reform.
As a result Cipfa has decided to 'give new focus to the debate' by setting
out some controversial issues.
Cipfa, with members in both public and private sectors, has been deeply
affected by government policies on privatisation within local government.
Mr Morris told a conference at the University of Bristol that competition
between the bodies was driving down standards because of the desire to
increase financial resources and student numbers.
He warned against the interests of the profession being aligned too closely
to the big firms' commercial interests. 'The two are not the same and can be
in direct conflict,' he said.
On party political affiliation he said: 'This is not in the long-run
interests of the profession, and it ought to be much more neutral in its
political posture.'
Mr Morris said that rising costs had forced the professional bodies to
compete to generate income, and they had had to take on regulatory roles in
conflict with the interests of their members.
He attacked the 'conservative education and training policies' of the bodies
and their reluctance to embrace change in the form of devolved or continuous
assessment.
'They are reluctant to move down the NVQ route and they are reluctant to
give authority over educational matters to other bodies which are
specialists in education, such as universities.'
With technical knowledge developing fast Mr Morris sees the need for regular
assessment of the membership, say every five years, to ensure standards are
maintained.
</TEXT>
