<HEADLINE>
FT  27 OCT 94 / World Trade News: Coface tightens Saudi terms
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ANDREW JACK
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   PARIS
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
France said yesterday it had toughened terms for providing export credit
guarantees to companies dealing with Saudi Arabia, following a reassessment
of the kingdom's ability to pay promptly. The government said that Coface,
the French export credit agency, was approving short-term credit assurance
(for less than three years) on a case-by-case basis but with increased
'vigilance'. NCM Credit Insurance, which handles 80 per cent of Britain's
short-term export credit guarantees, has already announced it is reducing
the availability of facilities for UK companies exporting to Saudi Arabia.
It said payments delays to exporters were continuing to worsen and expressed
concern at the 'very grave' financial situation. Last month Coface stopped
providing medium-term support for companies trading with the kingdom on the
basis of standard credit terms. It continues to provide medium-term support
to businesses for transactions payable in cash, provided the Saudis also
underwrite the contracts.
