<HEADLINE>
FT  27 OCT 94 / N Korea army chief may go
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JOHN BURTON
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   SEOUL
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
The arrival in France for medical treatment of Marshal Oh Jin-u, 77, North
Korea's defence minister, may provide an opportunity for Mr Kim Jong-il, the
country's new leader, to curb possible military opposition to his rule.
Marshal Oh, who ranks second behind Mr Kim, is believed to be suffering from
lung cancer and his trip to France indicates his condition has become
serious. He was a friend of the late President Kim Il-sung and is chief
representative of the conservative old guard that established North Korea in
the late 1940s. The defence ministry, in a show of independence, last month
publicly rejected a US demand for special inspections of suspected nuclear
facilities, which Pyongyang subsequently accepted in the recent accord.
Analysts believe Mr Kim may appoint Gen Oh Guk-ryol, who is seen as his
chief military supporter. Gen Oh advocates a more professional military by
reducing the role of political officers.
