<HEADLINE>
FT  27 OCT 94 / Hamilton linked to companies probed by SFO
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ROBERT PESTON, PEGGY HOLLINGER and WILLIAM LEWIS
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Mr Neil Hamilton, who resigned as corporate affairs minister on Tuesday, was
a director of a company linked to a group of companies investigated by the
Serious Fraud Office.
A colleague of Mr Hamilton said yesterday that Downing Street was likely to
have been made aware of the SFO probe and that this may have contributed to
Mr John Major's decision to ask him to resign. There is no suggestion that
Mr Hamilton himself has been investigated.
'The disclosure would have been particularly embarrassing to him, given that
he is corporate affairs minister at the DTI,' said a Conservative colleague.
From January 17 to September 30 1990, Mr Hamilton was a director of Plateau
Mining, a gold mining company. Plateau had previously been owned by
Robertson Group, the mining consultancy, whose activities have been examined
by the SFO as part of its probe into natural resource companies connected to
Midlands entrepreneur Mr Clive Smith.
Mr Hamilton joined Plateau's board when Robertson floated the company on the
Stock Exchange. He resigned when he joined the government as a whip.
Plateau's shares came to market at a price of 90p, valuing the group at
Pounds 16.8m. In August 1992, Plateau's shares were suspended at 3p and
eight months later it was taken over at 6p a share.
The SFO is investigating the flotations of Butte Mining and Richmond Oil and
Gas. When Butte bought properties in 1988, Robertson appraised the assets
and after the acquisition had a 14.9 per cent holding in Butte.
On Tuesday, Mr Hamilton was told at a meeting with Mr Michael Heseltine, the
trade secretary, and Mr Richard Ryder, the chief whip, that allegations had
been sent to Downing Street relating to Plateau.
Mr Heseltine and Mr Ryder told him they felt his ability to carry out his
duties would be impaired by the need to answer these allegations and others.
