<HEADLINE>
FT  27 OCT 94 / Citibank proposes limited liability for Lloyd's Names
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By RALPH ATKINS, Insurance Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
A plan that could bring further sweeping changes to Lloyd's of London by
allowing many Names to trade in the insurance market on the basis of limited
liability was unveiled yesterday.
Citibank, the subsidiary of US group Citicorp, announced proposals that
would enable Names to convert from unlimited liability - the
long-established system of trading - without breaking Lloyd's rules.
The proposals, drawn up with members' agencies which look after Names'
interests, could lead to a further reduction in the number of traditional
Names, the individuals whose assets have historically supported the Lloyd's
insurance market.
Names have been hit by heavy losses in recent years and the number actively
underwriting has fallen from 32,000 in 1988 to less than 18,000 this year.
Mr Peter Middleton, Lloyd's chief executive, said yesterday that most
Lloyd's Names may convert in the next few years - though higher returns
offered by unlimited liability would continue to attract a minority.
'There will be a strong caucus - perhaps 3,500 - who will opt to remain
exactly as they are, on unlimited liability,' he said.
Citibank's proposals await approval by Lloyd's authorities but have been
drawn up in consultation with its officials. The plan will be considered by
Lloyd's on November 4.
Main features include a 'reinsurance' agreement by which Names would
transfer liabilities outstanding on policies they have underwritten
previously to an individual company, or 'Name-Co'. This would not isolate
them completely from past exposures but offer some protection.
Lloyd's has agreed that NameCos should hold a minimum of Pounds 100,000 at
the insurance market, compared with the Pounds 1.5m required from companies
set up in the past few years to inject corporate capital into the market.
To make the scheme more attractive, Citibank has arranged for some of those
taking up the scheme to buy a separate reinsurance policy which will have
the effect of increasing their funds held at Lloyd's - allowing them to
underwrite more business.
If substantial numbers of Names transfer to limited liability, the process
could become unstoppable. A dwindling number of unlimited liability Names
would, in effect, become insurers of last resort. They might therefore want
to convert as well.
At an Association of Lloyd's Members conference yesterday, Mr Middleton said
to avoid that problem the insurance market needed transitional arrangements
leading to a strengthening of assets available to Lloyd's.
Lex, Page 20
</TEXT>
