<HEADLINE>
FT  26 OCT 94 / Japanese cabinet prepares for opening of rice market
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
The cabinet yesterday adopted a plan to spend Y6,010bn (Dollars 62bn) to
prepare rice farmers for the gradual opening of their market.
The package, prepared by the three parties of the ruling coalition, clears
the way for parliament to ratify the trade liberalisation bills needed to
comply with the Uruguay Round of the General Agreement on Tariffs and Trade.
Japan aims to ratify the Gatt accord in the present parliamentary session,
ending on December 3. As part of the accord, a previous government agreed
last year to import 4-8 per cent of its annual 10m tonne rice consumption
over the next six years, and replace import quotas with tariffs some time
after that. The farm aid package will be spent over the same period.
The aid programme was criticised yesterday for failing to do enough to
encourage large efficient farms, at the expense of traditional small paddy
fields. The government is bargaining that the cash will at least compensate
farmers for the opening of the rice market.
</TEXT>
