<HEADLINE>
FT  26 OCT 94 / International Company News: Conseco delays Kemper takeover
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By RICHARD WATERS
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   NEW YORK
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
Conseco, the US life insurance group, yesterday said it would not complete
its planned Dollars 2.7bn acquisition of Kemper this year, due to a delay in
lining up finance for the bid.
The news follows growing uncertainty in recent weeks about the financial
backing for the highly-leveraged transaction.
In spite of the delay, Conseco said its bid would go ahead, and that it was
still 'exploring' the sale of one or more of its life insurance company
holdings to reduce the debt portion of the deal.
'With or without asset sales, we remain confident that financing for the
acquisition of Kemper will be available on terms acceptable to Conseco,'
said Mr Stephen Hilbert, chairman.
If it does not sell assets, Conseco's high debt level after the acquisition
would almost certainly lead to a downgrade of its credit standing by the
rating agencies, adding to its borrowing costs.
The company has already received commitments from banks for Dollars 1.2bn of
debt to back the Kemper takeover. Under the terms of that loan, any cash
raised by the sale of the life company interests would be used to repay part
of the bank debt.
Conseco is also planning to begin selling Dollars 750m of junk bonds early
next month. This part of the fund-raising is backed by a letter from Morgan
Stanley, Conseco's adviser, which says it is 'highly confident' the money
can be raised. Although not legally a form of underwriting, the investment
bank's decision to stake its reputation on the success of the financing
implies a heavy commitment to the transaction.
The deal needs the approval of both companies' shareholders, regulators and
investors in Kemper's mutual funds. Conseco added that it would seek to
postpone a hearing by Illinois insurance regulators set for next Wednesday.
Kemper had third-quarter operating earnings of Dollars 32.7m on its
continuing operations, which before one-off factors were flat on last year.
</TEXT>
